stylometry: The easiest way to explain the logical upper limit is to look at it like a ceiling. In a room, nothing can go higher than the ceiling, it is a constraint.  It keeps you from going any higher.  This is the logical upper limit.  It is important to have one because if you didn't have a logical upper limit, the numbers could be endless, this is a way for solver to understand that the answer needs to be within a certain range of numbers. In cluster problems, the logical upper limit needed to be stated because otherwise there would be amounts of numbers that are not relateable to the problem at hand.
